{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637432"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17659"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17659"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.03,0.93,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24263"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ureter enters the bladder through the bladder wall in an oblique fashion, creating a one-way valve mechanism that is crucial for normal urinary tract function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the ureterovesical valve mechanism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regulates the rate of urine flow into the bladder","Prevents bladder emptying during ureteral peristalsis","Controls the timing of micturition","Prevents retrograde flow of urine from bladder to ureter","Maintains constant bladder pressure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevention of retrograde flow from bladder to ureter\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the ureterovesical valve mechanism. This is achieved through two main features: the oblique course of the ureter through the bladder wall and the compression of the intramural portion of the ureter by increased intravesical pressure during bladder filling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulating the rate of urine flow into the bladder\u003C/strong\u003E - The rate of urine flow is determined by ureteral peristalsis and kidney function, not by the ureterovesical valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing bladder emptying during ureteral peristalsis\u003C/strong\u003E - The internal and external urethral sphincters control bladder emptying, while the ureterovesical valve has no role in this process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls the timing of micturition\u003C/strong\u003E - The nervous system and urethral sphincters coordinate micturition timing, not the ureterovesical valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintaining constant bladder pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - The bladder naturally experiences pressure changes during filling and emptying cycles, which is not regulated by the ureterovesical valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis valve mechanism is essential for preventing vesicoureteral reflux, which can lead to kidney damage and urinary tract infections if compromised.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ureterovesical junction prevents urine reflux through both its oblique entry angle into the bladder and its muscular valve mechanism.","As the bladder fills, increased intravesical pressure compresses the intramural portion of the ureter, preventing reflux.","The one-way valve mechanism of the ureter is essential for preventing urinary tract infections and kidney damage."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17659"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T08:15:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T12:48:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75889"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descri